<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the child-task
    `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_casemgmt`.

    This table is the case-task subset of the AAP's three-table data model
    (AAP Section 0.5.7). It replaces the JPA entity AcmTask defined in
    com.armedia.acm.plugins.task.model.AcmTask
    (acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java), specifically the tiny
    six-field subset enumerated in AAP Section 0.5.7. The vast majority of
    AcmTask's ~60 fields (priority, attachment metadata, business-process
    info, percent-complete, workflow request IDs, document-under-review,
    documents-to-review, ECM container, participants, candidate claim
    groups, buckslip approval, rework instructions, outcome information,
    notification receivers, ad-hoc/completion flags, taskDurationInMillis,
    nextAssignee, legacySystemId, restriction flag, etc.) are intentionally
    OUT OF SCOPE per AAP Section 0.3.2 (no document management, no
    Activiti/BPMN workflow engine, no buckslip approval, no ECM, no
    business-process integration, no Outlook calendar, no ZyLAB matter
    integration, no notification engine).

    The six in-scope fields and their AcmTask source-field counterparts:
      - case        (Reference -> x_casemgmt_case)         <- attachedToObjectId + attachedToObjectType (when CASE_FILE)
      - subject     (String 255, mandatory)                <- title (with @Size(min=1) Bean Validation)
      - type        (Choice)                               <- type (free-form String in source; collapsed to choice)
      - status      (Choice: Open / In Progress / Closed)  <- status (with pendingStatus companion in source)
      - assigned_to (Reference -> sys_user, mandatory)     <- assignee (replaced username string lookup with reference)
      - due_date    (Date, mandatory)                      <- dueDate (with @NotNull)

    These six fields are NOT defined in this record - they are authored as
    separate sys_dictionary records in the sibling ../dictionary/ folder
    (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml, x_casemgmt_case_task_subject.xml,
    x_casemgmt_case_task_type.xml, x_casemgmt_case_task_status.xml,
    x_casemgmt_case_task_assigned_to.xml, x_casemgmt_case_task_due_date.xml).
    The choice value lists for type and status are authored in
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml (Investigation, Review,
    Follow-up, Other) and ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml (Open,
    In Progress, Closed) per AAP Section 0.5.1.

    This record authors ONLY table-level metadata (name, labels, parent
    class, scope linkage, auto-numbering reference, and access flags). The
    platform automatically inherits the standard sys_* audit columns
    (sys_id, sys_created_on, sys_created_by, sys_updated_on,
    sys_updated_by) by virtue of being a sys_db_object record.

    Constraints honored:
      - Scoped-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope; no global-scope writes.
      - Zero hardcoded sys_id literals in any reference field; sys_scope,
        sys_package, and number_ref all resolve by scope name via the
        `source` attribute. The sys_id element below is THIS record's own
        primary key (deterministic MD5 of the table name
        `x_casemgmt_case_task` = f9fd58b1a8c6ecc0cf653c0b50ecc5a3) and is
        not a reference to any other record.
      - super_class is EMPTY: this table extends NOTHING. Critically, it
        does NOT extend the OOB `task` table even though the source entity
        is named AcmTask and the conceptual mapping aligns with task
        semantics. Extending the OOB `task` table would (a) write to global
        scope and (b) inherit the OOB task table's ~60 columns (priority,
        state, due_date, etc.), creating massive scope creep and violating
        AAP Section 0.3.2's MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE. The platform still
        provides the standard sys_* audit columns because sys_db_object
        records always do.
      - extension_model is empty: this is a free-standing user-data table,
        not an extended table.
      - is_extendable is false: this POC table is not designed to be
        sub-classed.
      - create_access_controls is false: ServiceNow auto-creates a default
        ACL set when this is true. Since ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml
        enumerates a precise role x table x CRUD matrix that mirrors the
        case-table ACL pattern (case_manager full access; case_agent
        restricted to tasks whose parent case has the agent assigned;
        case_viewer read-only), the auto-generated ACLs would conflict and
        are explicitly suppressed here.
      - The reference target sys_user (for `assigned_to`) is an OOB
        ServiceNow table that this record does NOT modify. It is referenced
        ONLY via the dictionary entry in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_assigned_to.xml, never via
        super_class.
      - The concrete scope identifier casemgmt is used throughout per AAP convention; ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export. At Update Set import time, the platform
        resolves every `source="x_casemgmt"` reference
        against the scope's `name` field on sys_scope / sys_app rather than
        via sys_id, guaranteeing portability across PDIs.
      - ws_access is public: required because the portal's case-submission
        Scripted REST endpoint (per AAP Section 0.4.1, although the
        primary-write target is the parent case table) and any future
        agent-driven task-creation REST surface need access. The actual
        anonymous-write path goes through the case_submit endpoint, not
        directly here, but consistency with the case table's access flags
        keeps the role-based ACL stack working uniformly.

    Cross-Update-Set load ordering (per AAP Section 0.5.2):
      - This record MUST be loaded AFTER ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml and
        ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml.
      - This record MUST be loaded AFTER
        ../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (referenced by
        number_ref).
      - This record MUST be loaded AFTER ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
        because ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml (loaded after
        this record) creates a Reference column whose target is
        x_casemgmt_case.
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE all
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml records (they reference
        this table by `name`).
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE all
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml records.
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE the case state-machine flows in
        ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml because the
        validate_resolved_transition subflow performs a GlideRecord query
        against this table to enforce the "All tasks must be closed before
        resolving this case." rule (AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim).
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE the
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml Script
        Include because it queries this table.
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml (the report queries
        x_casemgmt_case_task by due_date and assigned_to).
      - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE all
        ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml records.
-->
